  <div id="suits-wrapper">
    <%= render "home/suit_wrapper" %>
  </div>
</div>

<nav id="sidebar">
</nav>

<script id="modal-template" type="text/x-handlebars-template">
  <a class="close-reveal-modal">&#215;</a>
  <h2>Classic Charcoal<span class="divider">&nbsp;//&nbsp;</span>$329</h2>
  <div class="six columns preview-wrapper">
    <ul class="modal-suit-preview three columns">
      <li><a href="#"><img src="<%= asset_path "products/suits/modal-suit-preview.png" %>"></a></li>
      <li><a href="#"><img src="<%= asset_path "products/suits/modal-suit-preview.png" %>"></a></li>
      <li><a href="#"><img src="<%= asset_path "products/suits/modal-suit-preview.png" %>"></a></li>
      <li><a href="#"><img src="<%= asset_path "products/suits/modal-suit-preview.png" %>"></a></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="magnify nine columns">
      <div class="large"></div>
      <img class="main small" src="<%= asset_path "products/suits/charcoal-grey.jpg" %>">
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="six columns">
    <p class="blurb">Bring a little flavor to your suit collection. The classic charcoal suit breaks the mold of the
      black and navy tradition without drawing a disapproving look from your stodgy old boss. Stay fly.</p>
    <div class="customizations">
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="lapel" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Lapel</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="notch">
          <h5>Notch</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/lapel-notch.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="peak">
          <h5>Peak</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/lapel-peak.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="narrow">
          <h5>Narrow</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/lapel-narrow.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>Notch lapels are the most widely used lapels and are a safe and stylish choice for any suit. Peak lapels add a
          little pizazz for those who want to stand out. TR tip: If you are unsure, go with the notch lapel, you donâ€™t
          necessarily want anything to distract from the perfect fit of your tailored suit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="buttons" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Buttons</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="1">
          <h5>One</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/buttons-one.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="2">
          <h5>Two</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/buttons-two.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="3">
          <h5>Three</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/buttons-three.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>The modern standard and a fashionable choice is the two button suit. four button suits fit more of a classic
          style and look great on taller guys. A one button suit is a very stylish option for those who want to be
          adventurous. TR tip: If you are going to add a vest, stick with the two button jacket.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="vents" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Vents</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="0">
          <h5>None</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vents-none.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="1">
          <h5>One</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vents-one.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="2">
          <h5>Two</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vents-two.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>Having two vents is the traditional, safe and stylish choice. One vent is a way to make your suit modern and
          sleek without distracting from the excellent fit (we love the single vent). TR tip: If you are a shorter guy,
          go ahead and get the double vent, the vertical vents help to draw the eye upward and elongate the body.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="pleats" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Pleats</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="0">
          <h5>None</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/pleats-none.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="1">
          <h5>One</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/pleats-one.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="2">
          <h5>Two</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/pleats-two.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>Pleats are typically associated with old-fashioned suits. If you are looking for a modern, trendier look, we
          recommend going with no pleats and no cuffs on the pants.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper two-item" data-type="pant-cuffs" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Cuffs</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option" data-option="0">
          <h5>None</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/cuffs-no.png" %>" class="cuffs">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option" data-option="1">
          <h5>Cuffs</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/cuffs-yes.png" %>" class="cuffs">
        </a>
        <p>Pant cuffs were a suit staple in previous decades, but unless you are going for an older, more classic look,
          we recommend sticking with no pant cuffs. It keeps the suit lines clean and sharp, keeping those heads on a
          swivel.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="fit" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Fit</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="0">
          <h5>Slim</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/fit-slim.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="1">
          <h5>Tailored</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/fit-tailored.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="2">
          <h5>Normal</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/fit-normal.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>The tailored fit is guaranteed to look great on most guys. A regular fit is great for guys with a fuller
          figure. And the slim fit is great for lean guys who want a very tight fitting suit and know they will not have
          any weight changes in the future. TR tip: Regardless of the fit option, our suits are tailored to your
          measurements, so slim or full-figured, your suit will look and feel great.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper two-item" data-type="lining" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Lining</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option">
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/lining.png" %>" class="lining">
        </a>
        <div class="customization-option linings"></div>
        <p>The most common selection is matching lining, which works with the suit to bring out the fabrics natural
          intrigue. Contrasting linings are a great choice if you want to add a little flash to your suit, making your
          suit stand out. Contrasting lining works well with more modern and trendier suits. TR tip: A unique lining is
          a great way to make your suit stand out and really separates your suit from the off-the-rack crowd; we
          recommend being bold.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper two-item" data-type="monogram" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Monogram</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option">
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/monogram.png" %>" class="monogram">
        </a>
        <div class="customization-option"></div>
        <p>Monogramming can be up to 15 characters, usually used for your name (i.e. 'Richard Feynman' or 'R.P.F.' or
          'R. Feynman'). It will show up on the inside of your jacket above the left breast pocket. Feel free to put
          whatever you want here, just keep in mind that people will see it when you are showing off your envy-inducing
          lining.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper two-item" data-type="advanced" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Advanced</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option">
          <h5>Functional Bouttoninere</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/bouttoniere.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option">
          <h5>Pick Stitching</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/pick-stitching.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>Need text here.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper" data-type="vest" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Vest</h3>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="three">
          <h5>Three Buttons</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vest-three.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="four">
          <h5>Four Buttons</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vest-four.png" %>">
        </a>
        <a href="#" class="customization-option four" data-option="five">
          <h5>Five Buttons</h5>
          <img src="<%= asset_path "customizations/vest-five.png" %>">
        </a>
        <p>Text here...</p>
      </div>
      <div class="customization-wrapper">
        <a href="#" class="button add-to-cart">Add to cart</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</script>

<script>
  $(function() {
    new TR.Views.Shop();
  });
</script>